Minervae quae Chalcioicos vocatur: the walls of this temple of Minerva were covered with plates of bronze; conse· quently the deity worshiped in the temple was called the “dweller in the bronze house.” Thucydides states that Pausanias ran into a small building within the sacred precinct, not into the temple itself. Not merely was it forbidden to seize or kill a person within a temple enclosure, but to allow a person to die there desecrated the spot ; hence they carried Pausanias out.
